Dimensional principles
1. Objects are points
An object is not a bag of attributes.
It is a point in a space of potential detail.

"car" is a point.

"engine" is a point.

"carburetor" is a point.

Details only exist when referenced.

2. Detail manifests on observation
You don’t define everything upfront.

When you talk about car, only X = "car" exists.

When you say “check the engine”, X = "engine" manifests.

When you say “inspect the carburetor”, X = "carburetor" manifests.

This mirrors how AI activates concepts: only what’s in focus is “alive.”

3. State is geometric, not procedural
Instead of:

text
do A
then B
then C
Dimensional Programming is:

text
X₀ --Y₀--> Z₀ (= X₁)
X₁ --Y₁--> Z₁ (= X₂)
X₂ --Y₂--> Z₂ ...
A chain of (identity, modifier) → state transitions.

4. Dimensional descent
You can “zoom in” by moving down a dimension:

X = "car"

then X = "engine"

then X = "carburetor"

Each step is a new point, not a field on a class.

Why this is AI‑native
LLMs and neural networks internally operate on:

vectors

manifolds

bilinear maps

attention over relationships

The mapping:

X → a point in embedding space

Y → a direction / transformation

Z → a new point (state)

This is exactly what the model is already doing.

Dimensional Programming doesn’t force AI to pretend to be a human programmer.
It gives AI a surface to move on that matches its internal math.

Practical benefits
Lower token/credit usage  
Only the current X and Y need to be in context, not the entire object tree.

Fewer hallucinations  
AI doesn’t invent unused attributes—nothing exists until referenced.

Incremental updates  
You update state (Z), not regenerate entire files or systems.

Natural explainability  
Behavior is a chain of (X, Y) → Z transitions—easy to trace and reason about.

Composable reasoning  
Z becomes the next X, enabling clean, chainable logic without global mutation.

Example: Support ticket
Traditional style
text
class Ticket {
  id
  status
  priority
  history
  ...
}
Every field must be defined, loaded, and maintained—even if unused.

Dimensional Programming
text
X = "ticket #4821"
Y = "user reports login failure"
Z = "ticket #4821.login_failure_reported"

X = Z
Y = "system requests logs"
Z = "ticket #4821.logs_requested"

X = Z
Y = "user uploads logs"
Z = "ticket #4821.logs_received"
No giant class.
No full object graph.
Just state transitions.

Example: Shopping cart
text
X = "cart"
Y = "add item: laptop"
Z = "cart.with_laptop"

X = Z
Y = "add item: mouse"
Z = "cart.with_laptop_and_mouse"

X = Z
Y = "remove item: mouse"
Z = "cart.with_laptop"
Again: one point, one modifier, one new state.

Implementation sketch
You can implement Dimensional Programming in any language as a simple state engine:

ts
type Identity = string;
type Modifier = string;
type State = string;

type Transition = (x: Identity, y: Modifier) => State;

const transition: Transition = (x, y) => `${x}.${y}`;

let X: Identity = "car";
let Y: Modifier = "running";
let Z: State = transition(X, Y); // "car.running"

X = Z;
Y = "overheating";
Z = transition(X, Y); // "car.running.overheating"
The paradigm is not the code—it’s the discipline:

always operate on the current X

never assume subcomponents unless referenced

treat every step as (X, Y) → Z, with Z → X for the next step

